      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, I see the issue. The memory leak is due to the fact that the `Transaction* current` is being created inside the loop but never being deleted. This is a classic case of a memory leak, where the allocated memory is not properly freed, leading to increasing memory usage with each iteration of the loop. In the world of goblins, it's like leaving a trail of breadcrumbs for every goblin that passes through your garden, and before you know it, you've got goblins everywhere, eating up your resources. To fix this, you need to ensure that each `Transaction* current` is deleted after it's been saved to the ledger. Here's how you can do that:\n\n```cpp\nvoid process_transactions(Transaction* incoming) {\n    for (int i = 0; i < incoming->count; ++i) {\n        Transaction* current = new Transaction(incoming->data[i]);\n        \n        // perform some complex logic\n        apply_interest(current);\n        verify_checksum(current);\n        \n        save_to_ledger(current);\n        // we need to keep track of these for a bit\n        active_transactions.push_back(current);\n        \n        // Don't forget to delete the current transaction after saving it\n        delete current;\n    }\n}\n```\n\nNow",
